This reverts commit e0aee64b719bf1d0e1e433d6584a1b27c2b4ed4a.

Add advanced chunking, chat session, and query enhancement

Introduces advanced semantic chunking (app/chunking.py), chat session management (app/chat.py), and query enhancement (app/query_enhancement.py). Expands supported file types and metadata extraction in ingest.py, improves document normalization and deduplication, and adds user-specific vectorstore paths in config.py and main.py. Enhances query logic with dynamic retrieval, reranking, and improved context formatting. Updated requirements.

Add tests for semantic chunking, config, and query enhancement

Introduces new test suites for enhanced semantic chunking (test_chunking.py), user workspace configuration (test_config.py), and advanced query processing (test_query.py). Expands test_ingest.py to cover additional file types, semantic chunking integration, and fallback logic. These changes improve test coverage for new and enhanced features.

Add verbose logging system and improve code formatting

Introduces a comprehensive verbose logging system controlled by a config flag and environment variable. Refactors logging calls across modules to support verbosity, adds new logging functions, and updates the query pipeline to provide more detailed progress and debug information in verbose mode. Also improves code formatting and consistency in several modules, and enhances query enhancement and document chunking logic.

Improve test reliability and patching in test suite

Clears LRU cache for model_exists in fixtures to prevent cached results from affecting tests. Updates patch target for SemanticChunker in test_ingest.py to correct module. Ensures check_model_availability is imported within each test in test_llm.py for isolation. Fixes fallback indicator assertion in test_query.py to be case-insensitive.

Improve error handling and loading UX for cold starts

Adds retry logic to backend database connection and enhances error responses with retry suggestions. Frontend now displays a dedicated loading screen for initial loads and improves error messaging and retry behavior. Apollo client configuration is updated for more robust network error handling, increased retry attempts, and longer timeouts to better support cold starts and transient failures.

issue.title: Fix IIS 500.1001 error by updating app.js to require server from actual repository location
issue.body:
## Problem

The application was failing with an IIS 500.1001 error during deployment. The root cause was that the entry point `app.js` was trying to require `./server.js`, but this file didn't exist in the root directory. The deployment logs showed:

```
💫 app.js loaded, requiring server.js...
💥 Failed to load server.js: Error: Cannot find module './server.js'
```

This resulted in an opaque IIS 500.1001 Internal Server Error when accessing the application.

## Root Cause Analysis

The deployment process (`build-and-deploy.ps1`) is designed to copy backend files from `apps/pitch/backend/` to the root directory, including `server.js`. However, the application was failing because this deployment step either didn't complete or the copied files were missing.

## Solution

Instead of depending on the deployment script to copy files correctly, this PR updates `app.js` to require the server directly from its actual location in the repository structure.

**Before:**
```javascript
const server = require('./server.js');  // ❌ Expects copied file
```

**After:**
```javascript
const server = require('./apps/pitch/backend/server.js');  // ✅ Uses actual location
```

## Benefits

- **Immediate fix**: Resolves the IIS 500.1001 error without waiting for deployment process fixes
- **More robust**: Eliminates dependency on deployment script file copying working correctly  
- **Zero breaking changes**: Maintains all existing server functionality and endpoints
- **Minimal change**: Only 4 lines modified in a single file
- **Future-proof**: Works regardless of deployment process changes

## Testing

- ✅ Server loads successfully without errors
- ✅ All endpoints respond correctly (`/simple-test`, `/health`, etc.)
- ✅ No impact on existing functionality
- ✅ Works in both development and deployment scenarios

This is a surgical fix that addresses the immediate production issue while maintaining full backward compatibility.

issue.title: Overamplification per stream?
issue.body:
Some apps produce inconsistent (e.g. too quiet) audio stream volumes (e.g. Chrome on Fedora Silverblue).

Would be nice to be able to go over a 100% volume to match them with the rest of the system.

Nowadays I'm solving it with `org.pulseaudio.pavucontrol`. I would like to have only 1 app for audio stream fine control.

comment.body:
I think EasyEffects isn't the best place for this. We probably will always have one pipeline for all apps. As explained in older issues per streams effects require a very big amount of changes.

What we could consider is doing the same Pavucontrol does and let volume values above 100% to be set. But I wonder if that is really the best solution to the problem you are describing. Why not just using the autogain plugin? It is what I do to handle this kind of situation.
